# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: gloire-class-ironclad
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/alma-class-ironclad] The ***Alma*-class ironclads** were a group of seven wooden-hulled, armored corvettes built for the French Navy in the mid to late 1860s.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/alma-class-ironclad] Three of the ships attempted to blockade Prussian ports in the Baltic Sea in 1870 during the Franco-Prussian War.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/alma-class-ironclad] Three others patrolled the North Sea and the Atlantic, while the last ship was en route to Japan when the war began and blockaded two small Prussian ships in a Japanese harbor.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/alma-class-ironclad] Afterwards they alternated periods of reserve and active commissions, many of them abroad.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/alma-class-ironclad] Three of the ships participated in the French occupation of Tunisia in 1881 while another helped to intimidate the Vietnamese Government into accepting status as a French protectorate and played a small role in the Sino-French War of 1884–85.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/alma-class-ironclad] The *Alma*-class ironclads were designed by Henri Dupuy de Lôme as improved versions of the armored corvette *Belliqueuse* suitable for foreign deployments.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/alma-class-ironclad] Unlike their predecessor the ships were true central battery ironclads as they were fitted with armored transverse bulkheads.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/alma-class-ironclad] The original plan for these ships was to have a two-deck battery with four 194-millimeter (7.6 in) guns on the battery deck and four 164-millimeter (6.5 in) guns mounted above them on the upper deck, one gun at each corner of the battery.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/alma-class-ironclad] This design was changed to substitute four barbettes for the upper battery, but the addition of armored bulkheads proved to be very heavy and the rear pair of barbettes had to be deleted to save weight.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/alma-class-ironclad] In partial compensation the 164-millimeter guns in the remaining forward barbettes were replaced by an additional pair of 194-millimeter guns.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/alma-class-ironclad] Like most ironclads of their era they were equipped with a metal-reinforced ram.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/alma-class-ironclad] The ships were built from the same general plan, but differed amongst themselves.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/alma-class-ironclad] Their crew numbered 316 officers and men.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/alma-class-ironclad] The *Alma*-class ships had a single horizontal return connecting-rod steam engine driving a single propeller.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/alma-class-ironclad] Their engine was powered by four oval boilers.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/alma-class-ironclad] Unlike the single funnels of the others, *Jeanne d'Arc* and *Thétis* had two funnels, mounted side by side.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/alma-class-ironclad] They were barque-rigged with three masts and had a sail area between 1,338–1,454 square meters (14,400–15,650 sq ft).
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/alma-class-ironclad] The ships mounted four of their 194-millimeter Modèle 1864 breech-loading guns in the central battery on the battery deck.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/alma-class-ironclad] The other two 194-millimeter guns were mounted in barbettes on the upper deck, sponsoned out over the sides of the ship.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/alma-class-ironclad] The four 120-millimeter (4.7 in) guns were also mounted on the upper deck.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/alma-class-ironclad] *Alma* is the only ship positively known to have exchanged her 194 mm guns for newer Modèle 1870 guns.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/alma-class-ironclad] The armor-piercing shell of the 20-caliber Mle 1870 gun weighed 165.3 pounds (75 kg) while the gun itself weighed 7.83 long tons (7.96 t).
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/alma-class-ironclad] The gun fired its shell at a muzzle velocity of 1,739 ft/s (530 m/s) and was credited with the ability to penetrate a nominal 12.5 inches (320 mm) of wrought iron armour at the muzzle.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/alma-class-ironclad] The guns could fire both solid shot and explosive shells.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/alma-class-ironclad] The *Alma*-class ships had a complete 150-millimeter (5.9 in) wrought iron waterline belt, approximately 2.4 meters (7.9 ft) high.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/alma-class-ironclad] The sides of the battery itself were armored with 120 millimeters (4.7 in) of wrought iron and the ends of the battery were closed by bulkheads of the same thickness.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/alma-class-ironclad] The barbette armor was 100 millimeters (3.9 in) thick, backed by 240 millimeters (9.4 in) of wood.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/alma-class-ironclad] The unarmored portions of their sides were protected by 15-millimeter (0.6 in) iron plates.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/alma-class-ironclad] During the Franco-Prussian War of 1870–71 *Thétis*, *Jeanne d'Arc* and *Armide* were assigned to the Northern Squadron that attempted to blockade Prussian ports on the Baltic until ordered to return to Cherbourg on 16 September 1870.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/alma-class-ironclad] *Montcalm*, *Atalante*, and *Reine Blanche* cruised the North Sea and *Montcalm* later captured the Prussian Barque *Union* and watched a Prussian corvette in Portuguese waters.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/alma-class-ironclad] *Alma* was en route to the Far East when the war began and she blockaded a pair of Prussian corvettes in Yokohama harbor once she arrived at Japan.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/alma-class-ironclad] After the end of the war many of the ships were placed in reserve or sent to foreign stations, often as the flagship.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/alma-class-ironclad] During the Third Carlist War of 1872–76 *Thétis*, *Reine Blanche* and *Jeanne d'Arc* spent time in Spanish waters where they could protect French citizens and interests.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/alma-class-ironclad] In 1875, the latter ship rammed and sank the dispatch vessel *Forfait*.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/alma-class-ironclad] On 3 July 1877 *Thétis* rammed *Reine Blanche* who had to be run ashore to prevent her from sinking.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/alma-class-ironclad] Further abroad *Reine Blanche* and *Alma* bombarded the Tunisian port of Sfax in July 1881 as part of the French occupation of Tunisia.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/alma-class-ironclad] *Atalante* participated in the Battle of Thuận An in August 1883.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/alma-class-ironclad] This was an attack by the French on the forts defending the mouth of the Perfume River, leading to the Vietnamese capital of Huế in an attempt to intimidate the Vietnamese government.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/alma-class-ironclad] During the Sino-French War of 1884–85 the ship was in Huế in early September 1884, but she carried Admiral Amédée Courbet to Keelung, Taiwan on 23 September.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] The ***Amiral Baudin* class** was a type of ironclad barbette ship of the French Navy built in the late 1870s and late 1880s.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] The class comprised two ships: *Amiral Baudin* and *Formidable*.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] After the Italian Navy began building a series of very large ironclads in the mid-1870s, public pressure on the French naval command to respond in kind prompted the design for the *Amiral Baudin* class.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] New, very large guns were developed to counter the weapons carried by the Italian ships; *Amiral Baudin* and *Formidable* were equipped with a main battery of three 370 mm (14.6 in) guns in three open barbettes, all on the centerline.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] Begun in 1879, work on the ships proceeded slowly and they were not finished until 1888–1889, shortly before the first pre-dreadnought battleships began to be built, which rendered older ironclads like the *'Amiral Baudin* class obsolete.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] In the aftermath of the Franco-Prussian War of 1870–1871, the French Navy embarked on a construction program to strengthen the fleet in 1872.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] By that time, the Italian *Regia Marina* (Royal Navy) had begun its own expansion program under the direction of Benedetto Brin, which included the construction of several very large ironclad warships of the *Duilio* and *Italia* classes, armed with 450 mm (17.7 in) 100-ton guns.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] The French initially viewed the ships as not worthy of concern, though by 1877, public pressure over the new Italian vessels prompted the Navy's *Conseil des Travaux* (Board of Construction) to design a response, the first of which was the barbette ship *Amiral Duperré*.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] Further pressure was placed on the French naval command by developments in very large guns abroad.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] In addition to the Italian 100-ton guns, the British Royal Navy was experimenting with 81-ton guns, the British firm Armstrong (which had developed the 100-ton gun) was designing a 160-ton gun, and the German firm Krupp was rumored to be working on a colossal 220-ton gun.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] At the time, the gun was seen as the primary weapon at sea, since the previously favored tactic of ramming an opponent had been rendered less feasible by the invention of self-propelled torpedoes.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] The Inspector General of Artillery submitted a report to the French Naval Minister, Léon Martin Fourichon, on 20 November 1876 that recommended a 120-ton gun with a bore diameter of around 440 mm (17 in), which would be able to penetrate the thickest armor then in production.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] As the power of guns continued to grow, thicker armor was needed to protect the ships; the full side armor of earlier ironclads could not be thickened without prohibitively increasing displacement.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] French designers differed from their Italian counterparts, opting to retain a complete albeit narrow waterline armor belt instead of Brin's solution, the citadel system supported by a closely compartmentalized layer.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] The French decision was driven by a desire to protect their ships' ability to maneuver, as the unarmored ends of the citadel ships could be easily damaged and flooded.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] Continued pressure from the Chamber of Deputies, particularly over the caliber of gun chosen for *Amiral Duperré*—340 mm (13 in) 48-ton weapons—led the designers to begin work on larger 100-ton guns for the next class, which became *Amiral Baudin* and *Formidable*.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] On 19 January 1878, Louis Pierre Alexis Pothuau, who had succeeded Fourichon as naval minister in 1877, issued a request to shipyards in Brest and Lorient for designs for a new first-rank ironclad armed with either 75-ton or 100-ton guns.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] He specified the armament could be carried in single barbettes or in twin-gun turrets, both of which were to receive 550 mm (22 in) of armor protection.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] The belt armor was to be of equal thickness.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] Speed was set at 14.5 knots (26.9 km/h; 16.7 mph) from a two-shaft propulsion system.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] He also directed that a sailing rig was not to be fitted.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] They were the first French capital ships to be designed without sails.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] During a meeting on 30 July, the *Conseil des Travaux* evaluated several designs and selected the one presented by the naval engineer Charles Godron.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] The design featured three 100-ton guns in individual barbettes, all on the centerline.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] Unlike their counterparts in other European navies, the French retained a secondary battery of medium caliber guns, and Godron incorporated a battery of twelve 138.6 mm (5.46 in) guns.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] The arrangement of the armament maximized broadside fire at the expense of end-on fire, reflecting the opinion of those who believed the torpedo had reduced the effectiveness of ramming attacks.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] The *Conseil* requested alterations to the design, which Pothuau approved on 7 September; he then forwarded the changes to Godron on the 20th.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] Godron completed his revised design on 6 November and submitted them to the Director of Material, Sabattier, who in turn presented in to Pothuau on 13 December.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] Pothuau approved it the same day and instructed the shipyards in Brest and Lorient to begin construction immediately.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] Three days later, Sabattier informed the Directorate of Artillery to begin work on the new 100-ton guns.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] The French 100-ton gun, with a 370 mm (14.6 in) bore diameter, prompted the *Conseil des Travaux* to call for an even larger 120-ton weapon, but the 100-ton gun was retained for the new ships.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] Though the ships were intended to carry the new 100-ton guns, problems aboard other vessels with new 76-ton guns prompted the naval command to abandon the as-yet untested 100-ton weapons.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] A modified version of the 76-ton gun with a longer barrel that had been adapted to use new propellant charges was developed; these changes gave it higher muzzle velocity, which allowed its shells to penetrate as well as the 100-ton gun had been expected to perform.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] *Amiral Baudin* and *Formidable* had already begun construction by the time these new guns had been developed, so they were simply substituted for the larger guns on a one-for-one basis.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] The class suffered from significant design faults, most significantly the arrangement of the guns; because they were placed on the centerline, they were arranged for fighting on the broadside.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] But their short belt, which was almost completely submerged under service conditions, did not sufficiently protect them from damage.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] At the time of their completion, they were the most powerful vessels in the French fleet despite their flaws.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] The *Amiral Baudin* design proved to be successful and led to the derivative ironclad *Hoche* and three-ship *Marceau* class.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] The ships' period as state-of-the-art capital proved to be very brief; they were completed in 1888 and 1889, just before Britain passed the Naval Defence Act of 1889, authorizing the *Royal Sovereign* class of what would become known as pre-dreadnought battleships.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] These were significantly more powerful vessels than the ironclad vessels of the 1870s and 1880s.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] The French in turn responded with their Naval Law of 1890, laying down a series of experimental pre-dreadnoughts beginning with *Charles Martel* that year.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] The *Amiral Baudin*-class ships were 97.99 m (321 ft 6 in) long between perpendiculars, 101.4 m (332 ft 8 in) long at the waterline, and 105 m (343 ft) long overall.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] They had a beam of 21.34 m (70 ft) and a draft of 8.46 m (27 ft 9 in).
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] The ships had a fairly minimal superstructure, with a light conning tower with an open bridge.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] They were fitted with a pair of pole masts equipped with spotting tops for their main battery guns.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] The hull was constructed with transverse and longitudinal steel frames and had a double bottom to reduce the risk of flooding.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] The hull featured a pronounced tumblehome shape common to French capital ships of the period, and they incorporated a ram bow.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] Their crews consisted of 625 officers and enlisted men.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] Steering was controlled by a single rudder.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] The ships were difficult to maneuver and they rolled badly in service, particularly in a beam sea, making them poor gun platforms.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] The ships' propulsion machinery consisted of a pair of two-shaft, vertical compound steam engines that each drove a screw propeller.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] The engines were placed in separate engine rooms, divided by a watertight bulkhead.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] Steam for the engines was provided by twelve coal-burning fire-tube boilers, which were split into four watertight boiler rooms and were ducted into a single, large funnel just aft of the conning tower.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] In service, *Formidable* was only capable of reaching a maximum of 15.2 knots (28.2 km/h; 17.5 mph), while *Amiral Baudin* reached a maximum speed of 15.22 knots (28.19 km/h; 17.51 mph) on her initial trials in 1888.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] Coal storage amounted to 790 long tons (800 t).
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] The ships' main armament consisted of three 370 mm, 28-caliber M1875–79 breechloading guns mounted in individual barbette mounts, one forward, one amidships, and one aft, all on the centerline.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] These had been modified from the original M1875 gun to use a new propellant that burned slower than traditional black powder, producing higher muzzle velocity and improved penetration.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] They had a very slow rate of fire, taking ten minutes to reload after every shot, common for guns of the era.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] By 1895, the rate of fire had been improved to one shot every seven minutes, and new loading equipment installed in 1903 had increased the rate further, to three minutes and twenty seconds between shots.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] These guns were supported by a secondary battery of four 163 mm (6.4 in) and eight or ten 138 mm (5.4 in) guns, all carried in individual pivot mounts.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] The 163 mm guns were placed in sponsons in the main deck, two forward and two aft, while the 138 mm guns were in open mounts atop the main deck.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] These guns had a rate of fire of one shot per minute, but the blast effects of the main battery guns were so severe that the secondary gun crews had to be withdrawn from their positions when they were fired.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] For defense against torpedo boats, *Amiral Baudin* carried four 47 mm (1.9 in) 3-pounder guns, one 47 mm 3-pounder Hotchkiss revolver cannon, and fourteen 37 mm (1.5 in) 1-pounder Hotchkiss revolvers, all in individual mounts.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] *Formidable* had one of the 47 mm guns and twelve of the 47 mm revolvers, along with eighteen of the 1-pounder revolver cannon.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] Their armament was rounded out with six 381 mm (15 in) torpedo tubes in above-water mounts.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] The ships were protected with a combination of mild steel and compound armor produced by Schneider-Creusot; their belt extended for the entire length of the hull and was composed of steel.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] The belt was intended to extend from 1.6 m (5 ft 3 in) below the waterline to 0.90 m (2 ft 11 in) above, but overloading of the ship caused all but 0.30 m (1 ft) to be submerged, leaving most of the hull exposed to enemy fire.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] This seriously degraded the effectiveness of the armor and was a major weakness of the *Amiral Baudin* design.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] In the central portion, where it protected the propulsion machinery spaces and ammunition magazines, the belt was 559 mm (22 in) thick; at the top edge, it tapered slightly to 508 mm (20 in), while at the lower edge, it was reduced to 406 mm (16 in).
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] Forward, the belt reduced to 356 to 394 mm (14 to 15.5 in) and aft it was uniformly 356 mm thick.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] The upper edge of the belt was connected to the armor deck, which was 80 mm (3 in) thick at the bow and stern and 100 mm (3.9 in) where it covered the machinery spaces.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] The deck was layered directly on 20 mm (0.79 in) deck plating.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] The barbettes for the main battery were composed of 400 mm of compound armor and the supporting tubes that protected the ammunition hoists were the same thickness, but were of steel construction.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] The guns themselves were protected from shell splinters by armored hoods that were 80 mm (3.1 in) thick.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] Between 1896 and 1898, both members of the class were modernized to improve their fighting characteristics as part of a large-scale program in the late 1890s to update some fifteen ironclads that had been completed over the previous decade.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] The most significant alterations concerned the ships' armament.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] The central main battery gun was removed, along with its barbette, and a new, lightly armored battery for the 163 mm guns was erected in its place.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] These guns were removed from their hull sponsons and quick-firing versions were installed in the new battery.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] Quick-firing 138 mm guns were also installed in place of their older versions.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] Her light battery was revised to a pair of 65 mm (2.6 in) guns, twenty 47 mm guns, six 37 mm guns, and six 37 mm revolver cannon.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] The light guns were placed in fighting tops on the masts and on the superstructure.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] Both ships had two of their torpedo tubes removed during the refit.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] The original light conning towers were replaced with armored structures that had 60 mm (2.4 in) of chrome steel on 20 mm of plating and 80 mm of armor on the fronts.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] Many of the French ironclads had excessively heavy superstructures that needed to be reduced, but the minimalist structures of the *Amiral Baudin*s received only minor alterations, including enlarged bridge structures; *Amiral Baudin* had an enclosed bridge installed.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] Their light, pole fore masts were replaced with heavier military masts to support the additional light guns, while *Amiral Baudin* had her main mast shortened; *Formidable* retained her original main mast.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] They also received new water-tube boilers that improved performance.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] As a result of the alterations, the ships' crews increased slightly to 650 officers and enlisted men.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] As more modern pre-dreadnought battleships began to enter the fleet by the late 1890s, *Amiral Baudin* and *Formidable* were transferred from the Mediterranean Fleet—the main French naval force—to the less strategically significant Northern Squadron in 1899.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] There, the normal routine of training exercises continued as in earlier years, including joint maneuvers with the Mediterranean Fleet.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] They both remained in service until 1902, when *Amiral Baudin* was transferred to the Reserve Squadron of the Mediterranean Fleet.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] *Formidable* lingered on with the Northern Squadron that year, but was demobilized as well in 1903.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] *Formidable* was briefly reactivated in 1904 to temporarily replace another vessel, but quickly returned to reserve; neither vessel saw further active service and *Amiral Baudin* was converted into a hulk in 1909.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/amiral-baudin-class-ironclad] *Formidable* was stricken from the naval register in 1911 and broken up, but *Amiral Baudin*'s fate is unknown.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] A **frigate** (/ˈfrɪɡɪt/) is a type of warship.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] In different eras, the roles and capabilities of ships classified as frigates have varied.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] In the 17th to early 18th centuries the term "frigate" was loosely given to any full-rigged ship built for speed and manoeuvrability and intended for scouting, escort or patrol.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] By the second quarter of the 18th century, what is regarded as the "true frigate" was developed in France and subsequently copied by other navies.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] This type of vessel was characterised by a long sleek design with a single gun deck of 28 and 36 cannons, and an unarmed deck below used for berthing the crew.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] In the mid-nineteenth century the definition of *frigate* was expanded to include the early ironclad warships, which also had a single gun deck.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] However, later developments in ironclad ships rendered the designation obsolete and the term fell out of favour in navies worldwide.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] The term was reintroduced in the Second World War to describe a seagoing escort ship of intermediate size between a corvette and a destroyer.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] After the war, this definition has gradually expanded to include many different kinds of vessels, from large ocean-going anti-submarine warfare ships to corvettes, destroyers, and nuclear-powered guided-missile cruisers.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] The etymology of the word (Italian: *fregata*; Dutch: *fregat*; Spanish/Catalan/Portuguese/Sicilian: *fragata*; French: *frégate*; German: *Fregatte*) remains uncertain, although it may have originated as a corruption of *aphractus*, a Latin word for an open vessel with no lower deck.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] *Aphractus*, in turn, derived from the Ancient Greek phrase ἄφρακτος ναῦς (*aphraktos naus*) – "undefended ship".
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] The term *frigate* originated in the Mediterranean in the late 16th century, referring to a lighter galley-type warship with oars, sails and a light armament, built for speed and manoeuvrability.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] The first recorded usage of the term seems to date from 1562, when Alonso Pérez, Duke of Medina Sidonia armed a galley fleet complemented with vessels called *fragatas* which were claimed to be invented by him.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] These frigates proved impractical and were retired soon.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] Other sources state Medina Sidonia actually credited Álvaro de Bazán, Marquis of Santa Cruz with their invention.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] The term was later used as an alternate name for the *galizabra*, a kind of galleass built by Álvaro's brother Alonso in 1584 as a cross between a galley and a zabra.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] In 1583, during the Eighty Years' War of 1568–1648, Habsburg Spain recovered the southern Netherlands from the Protestant rebels.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] This soon resulted in the use of the occupied ports as bases for privateers, the "Dunkirkers", to attack the shipping of the Dutch and their allies.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] To achieve this the Dunkirkers developed small, manoeuvrable, sailing vessels that came to be referred to as frigates.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] In French, the term *frigate* gave rise to a verb – *frégater*, meaning 'to build long and low', and to an adjective, adding more confusion.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] Even the huge English *Sovereign of the Seas* could be described as "a delicate frigate" by a contemporary after her upper decks were reduced in 1651.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] The navy of the Dutch Republic became the first navy to build the larger ocean-going frigates.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] The Dutch navy had three principal tasks in the struggle against Spain: to protect Dutch merchant ships at sea, to blockade the ports of Spanish-held Flanders to damage trade and halt enemy privateering, and to fight the Spanish fleet and prevent troop landings.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] The first two tasks required speed, shallowness of draft for the shallow waters around the Netherlands, and the ability to carry sufficient supplies to maintain a blockade.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] The third task required heavy armament, sufficient to stand up to the Spanish fleet.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] The first of the larger battle-capable frigates were built around 1600 at Hoorn in Holland.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] By the later stages of the Eighty Years' War (1568–1648) the Dutch had switched entirely from the heavier ships still used by the English and Spanish to the lighter frigates, carrying around 40 guns and weighing around 300 tons.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] In the 17th century, the term *fregat* in the Dutch Navy described any oceangoing warship carrying fewer than 40 guns.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] The effectiveness of the Dutch frigates became most evident in the Battle of the Downs in 1639, encouraging most other navies, especially the English, to adopt similar designs.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] The fleets built by the Commonwealth of England in the 1650s generally consisted of ships described as "frigates", the largest of which were two-decker "great frigates" of the third rate.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] Carrying 60 guns, these vessels were as big and capable as "great ships" of the time; however, most other frigates at the time were used as "cruisers": independent fast ships.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] The term "frigate" implied a long hull-design, which relates directly to speed (see hull speed) and which also, in turn, helped the development of the broadside tactic in naval warfare.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] In the 17th century the term 'frigate' was sometimes applied very loosely and could be used for any warship.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] At this time, a further design evolved, reintroducing oars and resulting in galley frigates such as HMS *Charles Galley* of 1676, which was rated as a 32-gun fifth-rate but also had a bank of 40 oars set below the upper deck that could propel the ship in the absence of a favourable wind.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] In Danish, the word "fregat" often applied to warships carrying as few as 16 guns, such as HMS *Falcon*, which the British classified as a sloop.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] Under the rating system of the Royal Navy, by the middle of the 18th century, the term "frigate" was technically restricted to single-decked ships of the fifth rate, though small 28-gun frigates were classed as sixth rate.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] The classic sailing frigate, or "true frigate", well-known today for its role in the Napoleonic Wars, can be traced back to French developments in the second quarter of the 18th century.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] The French-built *Médée* of 1740 is often regarded as the first example of this type.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] These ships were square-rigged and carried all their main guns on a single continuous upper deck.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] The lower deck, known as the "gun deck", now carried no armament, and functioned as a "berth deck" where the crew lived, and was in fact placed below the waterline of the new frigates.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] The typical earlier cruiser had a partially armed lower deck, from which it was known as a "half-battery" or *demi-batterie* ship.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] Removing the guns from this deck allowed the height of the hull upperworks to be lowered, giving the resulting "true-frigate" much improved sailing qualities.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] The Royal Navy captured a number of the new French frigates, including *Médée*, during the War of the Austrian Succession (1740–1748) and the British were impressed by them, particularly for their inshore handling capabilities.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] They soon built copies (ordered in 1747), based on a French privateer named *Tygre*, and started to adapt the type to their own needs, setting the standard for other frigates as the leading naval power.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] However, most ships of this size were called "ship sloops".
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] A total of fifty-nine French sailing frigates were built between 1777 and 1790, with a standard design averaging a hull length of 135 ft (41 m) and an average draught of 13 ft (4.0 m).
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] The new frigates recorded sailing speeds of up to 14 knots (26 km/h; 16 mph), significantly faster than their predecessor vessels.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] In 1778, the British Admiralty introduced a larger "heavy" frigate, with a main battery of twenty-six or twenty-eight 18-pounder guns (with smaller guns carried on the quarterdeck and forecastle).
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] This move may reflect the naval conditions at the time; with both France and Spain as enemies, the usual British preponderance in ship numbers was no longer the case and there was pressure on the British to produce cruisers of individually greater force.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] In reply, the first French 18-pounder frigates were laid down in 1781.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] The 18-pounder frigate eventually became the standard frigate of the French Revolutionary and Napoleonic Wars.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] The British produced larger, 38-gun, and slightly smaller, 36-gun, versions and also a 32-gun design that can be considered an 'economy version'.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] The 32-gun frigates also had the advantage that they could be built by the many smaller, less-specialised shipbuilders.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] Frigates could (and usually did) additionally carry smaller carriage-mounted guns on their quarterdecks and forecastles (the superstructures above the upper deck).
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] In 1778 the Carron Iron Company of Scotland produced a naval gun which would revolutionise the armament of smaller naval vessels, including the frigate.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] The carronade was a large calibre, short-barrelled naval cannon which was light, quick to reload and needed a smaller crew than a conventional long gun.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] Due to its lightness it could be mounted on the forecastle and quarterdeck of frigates.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] It greatly increased the firepower, measured in weight of metal (the combined weight of all projectiles fired in one broadside), of these vessels.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] The disadvantages of the carronade were that it had a much shorter range and was less accurate than a long gun.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] The British quickly saw the advantages of the new weapon and soon employed it on a wide scale.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] The US Navy also copied the design soon after its appearance.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] The French and other nations eventually adopted variations of the weapon in succeeding decades.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] The typical heavy frigate had a main armament of 18-pounder long guns, plus 32-pounder carronades mounted on its upper decks.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] The first "super-heavy frigates", armed with 24-pounder long guns, were built by the naval architect F H Chapman for the Swedish navy in 1782.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] Because of a shortage of ships-of-the-line, the Swedes wanted these frigates, the *Bellona* class, to be able to stand in the battle line in an emergency.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] It is not known whether the French were seeking to produce very potent cruisers or merely to address stability problems in old ships.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] The British, alarmed by the prospect of these powerful heavy frigates, responded by rasée-ing three of their smaller 64-gun battleships, including *Indefatigable*, which went on to have a very successful career as a frigate.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] At this time the British also built a few 24-pounder-armed large frigates, the most successful of which was HMS *Endymion* (1,277 tons).
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] In 1797, three of the United States Navy's first six major ships were rated as 44-gun frigates, which operationally carried fifty-six to sixty 24-pounder long guns and 32-pounder or 42-pounder carronades on two decks; they were exceptionally powerful.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] USS *Constitution*, preserved as a museum ship by the US Navy, is the oldest commissioned warship afloat, and is a surviving example of a frigate from the Age of Sail.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] *Constitution* and her sister ships *President* and *United States* were created in a response to deal with the Barbary Coast pirates and in conjunction with the Naval Act of 1794.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] Joshua Humphreys proposed that only live oak, a tree that grew only in America, should be used to build these ships.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] The Admiralty, concerned by repeated defeats in single-ship actions, responded to the success of the American 44s in three ways.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] They built a class of conventional 40-gun, 24-pounder armed frigates on the lines of *Endymion*.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] They cut down three old 74-gun Ships-of-the-Line into *rasées*, producing frigates with a 32-pounder main armament, supplemented by 42-pounder carronades.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] These had an armament that far exceeded the power of the American ships.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] Finally, *Leander* and *Newcastle*, 1,500-ton spar-decked frigates (with an enclosed waist, giving a continuous line of guns from bow to stern at the level of the quarterdeck/forecastle), were built, which were an almost exact match in size and firepower to the American 44-gun frigates.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] Frigates were perhaps the hardest-worked of warship types during the Age of Sail.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] While smaller than a ship-of-the-line, they were formidable opponents for the large numbers of sloops and gunboats, not to mention privateers or merchantmen.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] Able to carry six months' stores, they had very long range; and vessels larger than frigates were considered too valuable to operate independently.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] Frigates scouted for the fleet, went on commerce-raiding missions and patrols, and conveyed messages and dignitaries.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] Usually, frigates would fight in small numbers or singly against other frigates.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] They would avoid contact with ships-of-the-line; even in the midst of a fleet engagement it was bad etiquette for a ship of the line to fire on an enemy frigate which had not fired first.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] Frigates were involved in fleet battles, often as "repeating frigates".
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] In the smoke and confusion of battle, signals made by the fleet commander, whose flagship might be in the thick of the fighting, might be missed by the other ships of the fleet.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] Frigates were therefore stationed to windward or leeward of the main line of battle, and had to maintain a clear line of sight to the commander's flagship.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] Signals from the flagship were then repeated by the frigates, which themselves standing out of the line and clear from the smoke and disorder of battle, could be more easily seen by the other ships of the fleet.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] If damage or loss of masts prevented the flagship from making clear conventional signals, the repeating frigates could interpret them and hoist their own in the correct manner, passing on the commander's instructions clearly.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] For officers in the Royal Navy, a frigate was a desirable posting.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] Frigates often saw action, which meant a greater chance of glory, promotion, and prize money.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] Unlike larger ships that were placed in ordinary, frigates were kept in service in peacetime as a cost-saving measure and to provide experience to frigate captains and officers which would be useful in wartime.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] Frigates could also carry marines for boarding enemy ships or for operations on shore; in 1832, the frigate USS *Potomac* landed a party of 282 sailors and Marines ashore in the US Navy's first Sumatran expedition.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] Frigates remained a crucial element of navies until the mid-19th century.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] The first ironclads were classified as "frigates" because of the number of guns they carried.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] However, terminology changed as iron and steam became the norm, and the role of the frigate was assumed first by the protected cruiser and then by the light cruiser.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] Frigates are often the vessel of choice in historical naval novels due to their relative freedom compared to ships-of-the-line (kept for fleet actions) and smaller vessels (generally assigned to a home port and less widely ranging).
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] For example, the Patrick O'Brian Aubrey–Maturin series, C.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] Forester's Horatio Hornblower series and Alexander Kent's Richard Bolitho series.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] The 2003 film *Master and Commander: The Far Side of the World* features a reconstructed historic frigate, HMS *Rose*, to depict Aubrey's frigate HMS *Surprise*.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] Vessels classed as frigates continued to play a great role in navies with the adoption of steam power in the 19th century.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] In the 1830s, navies experimented with large paddle steamers equipped with large guns mounted on one deck, which were termed "paddle frigates".
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] From the mid-1840s on, frigates which more closely resembled the traditional sailing frigate were built with steam engines and screw propellers.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] These "screw frigates", built first of wood and later of iron, continued to perform the traditional role of the frigate until late in the 19th century.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] From 1859, armour was added to ships based on existing frigate and ship of the line designs.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] The additional weight of the armour on these first ironclad warships meant that they could have only one gun deck, and they were technically frigates, even though they were more powerful than existing ships-of-the-line and occupied the same strategic role.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] The phrase "armoured frigate" remained in use for some time to denote a sail-equipped, broadside-firing type of ironclad.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] The first such ship was the revolutionary Marine Nationale wooden-hulled *Gloire*, protected by 12 cm-thick (4.7 in) armour plates.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] The British response was HMS *Warrior* of the Warrior-class ironclads, launched in 1860.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] With her iron hull, steam engines propelling the 9,137 ton vessel to speeds of up to 14 knots and rifled breechloading 110-pdr guns, *Warrior* is the ancestor of all modern warships.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] During the 1880s, as warship design shifted from iron to steel and cruising warships without sails started to appear, the term "frigate" fell out of use.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] Vessels with armoured sides were designated as "battleships" or "armoured cruisers", while "protected cruisers" only possessed an armoured deck, and unarmoured vessels, including frigates and sloops, were classified as "unprotected cruisers".
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] Modern frigates are related to earlier frigates only by name.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] The term "frigate" was readopted during the Second World War by the British Royal Navy to describe an anti-submarine escort vessel that was larger than a corvette (based on a mercantile design), while smaller than a destroyer.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] The vessels were originally to be termed "twin screw corvettes" until the Royal Canadian Navy suggested to the British re-introducing the term "frigate" for the significantly enlarged vessels.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] Frigates, termed destroyer escorts by the US at the time, are less expensive to build and maintain than larger destroyers and cruisers.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] 22 of these were reclassified as frigates after the war, as were the remaining 24 smaller Castle-class corvettes.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] The frigate was introduced to remedy some of the shortcomings inherent in the Flower-class corvette design: limited armament, a hull form not suited to open-ocean work, a single shaft which limited speed and manoeuvrability, and a lack of range.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] The frigate was designed and built to the same mercantile construction standards (scantlings) as the corvette, allowing manufacture by yards unused to warship construction.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] The first frigates of the River class (1941) were essentially two sets of corvette machinery in one larger hull, armed with the latest Hedgehog anti-submarine weapon.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] The frigate possessed less offensive firepower and speed than a destroyer, including an escort destroyer, but such qualities were not required for anti-submarine warfare.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] Submarines were slow while submerged, and ASDIC sets did not operate effectively at speeds of over 20 knots (23 mph; 37 km/h).
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] Rather, the frigate was an austere and weatherly vessel suitable for mass-construction and fitted with the latest innovations in anti-submarine warfare.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] As the frigate was intended purely for convoy duties, and not to deploy with the fleet, it had limited range and speed.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] It was not until the Royal Navy's Bay class of 1944 that a British design classified as a "frigate" was produced for fleet use, although it still suffered from limited speed.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] These anti-aircraft frigates, built on incomplete Loch-class frigate hulls, were similar to the United States Navy's destroyer escorts (DE), although the latter had greater speed and offensive armament to better suit them to fleet deployments.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] The destroyer escort concept came from design studies by the General Board of the United States Navy in 1940, as modified by requirements established by a British commission in 1941 prior to the American entry into the war, for deep-water escorts.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] The American-built destroyer escorts serving in the Royal Navy were rated as Captain-class frigates.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] Navy's two Canadian-built *Asheville*-class and 96 British-influenced, American-built *Tacoma*-class frigates that followed originally were classified as "patrol gunboats" (PG) in the U.S.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] Navy but on 15 April 1943 were all reclassified as **patrol frigates (PF)**.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] The introduction of the surface-to-air missile after World War II made relatively small ships effective for anti-aircraft warfare: the "guided-missile frigate".
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] In the US navy, these vessels were called "ocean escorts" and designated "DE" or "DEG" until 1975 – a holdover from the World War II destroyer escort or "DE".
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] While the Royal Navy used similar designations for their warships built in the 1950s, they maintained the use of the term "frigate"; in the 1990s the RCN re-introduced the frigate designation.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] Likewise, the French Navy refers to missile-equipped ships, up to cruiser-sized ships (*Suffren*, *Tourville*, and Horizon classes), by the name of "frégate", while smaller units are named *aviso*.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] The Soviet Navy used the term "guard-ship" (*сторожевой корабль*).
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] From the 1950s to the 1970s, the United States Navy commissioned ships classed as guided-missile frigates (hull classification symbol DLG or DLGN, literally meaning guided-missile destroyer leaders), which were actually anti-aircraft warfare cruisers built on destroyer-style hulls.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] These had one or two twin launchers per ship for the RIM-2 Terrier missile, upgraded to the RIM-67 Standard ER missile in the 1980s.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] This type of ship was intended primarily to defend aircraft carriers against anti-ship cruise missiles, augmenting and eventually replacing converted World War II cruisers (CAG/CLG/CG) in this role.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] The guided-missile frigates also had an anti-submarine capability that most of the World War II cruiser conversions lacked.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] Some of these ships – *Bainbridge* and *Truxtun* along with the *California* and *Virginia* classes – were nuclear-powered (DLGN).
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] These "frigates" were roughly mid-way in size between cruisers and destroyers.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] This was similar to the use of the term "frigate" during the age of sail during which it referred to a medium-sized warship, but it was inconsistent with conventions used by other contemporary navies which regarded frigates as being smaller than destroyers.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] In the late 1970s, as a gradual successor to the *Knox* frigates, the US Navy introduced the 51-ship *Oliver Hazard Perry*-class guided-missile frigates (FFG), the last of which was decommissioned in 2015, although some serve in other navies.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] By 1995 the older guided-missile cruisers and destroyers were replaced by the *Ticonderoga*-class cruisers and *Arleigh Burke*-class destroyers.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] One of the most successful post-1945 designs was the British *Leander*-class frigate, which was used by several navies.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] Laid down in 1959, the *Leander* class was based on the previous Type 12 anti-submarine frigate but equipped for anti-aircraft use as well.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] They were used by the UK into the 1990s, at which point some were sold on to other navies.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] The *Leander* design, or improved versions of it, were licence-built for other navies as well.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] Nearly all modern frigates are equipped with some form of offensive or defensive missiles, and as such are rated as guided-missile frigates (FFG).
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] Improvements in surface-to-air missiles (e.g., the Eurosam Aster 15) allow modern guided-missile frigates to form the core of many modern navies and to be used as a fleet defence platform, without the need for specialised anti-air warfare frigates.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] They can thus provide theatre wide air and missile defence for forces such as a carrier battle group and typically serve this function".
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] By contrast the smaller "frigates are thus usually used as escort vessels to protect sea lines of communication or as an auxiliary component of a strike group".
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] The largest and most powerful destroyers, such as the *Ticonderoga*-class cruisers, are often classified as cruisers due to their extra armament and facilities to serve as fleet flagships.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] The Royal Navy Type 61 (*Salisbury* class) were "air direction" frigates equipped to track aircraft.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] To this end they had less armament than the Type 41 (*Leopard*-class) air-defence frigates built on the same hull.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] Multi-role frigates such as the MEKO 200, *Anzac* and *Halifax* classes are designed for navies needing warships deployed in a variety of situations that a general frigate class would not be able to fulfil, and not requiring destroyers.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] At the opposite end of the spectrum, some frigates are specialised for anti-submarine warfare.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] Increasing submarine speeds towards the end of World War II (see German Type XXI submarine) greatly reduced the margin of speed superiority of frigate over submarine.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] The frigate could no longer be slow and powered by mercantile machinery, and consequently postwar frigates such as the *Whitby* class were faster.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] Such ships carry improved sonar equipment, such as the variable depth sonar or towed array, and specialised weapons such as torpedoes, forward-throwing weapons such as Limbo and missile-carried anti-submarine torpedoes such as ASROC or Ikara.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] The Royal Navy's original Type 22 frigate is an example of a specialised anti-submarine warfare frigate, though it also has Sea Wolf surface-to-air missiles for point defence plus Exocet surface-to-surface missiles for limited offensive capability.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] Especially for anti-submarine warfare, most modern frigates have a landing deck and hangar aft to operate helicopters, eliminating the need for the frigate to close with unknown sub-surface threats, and using fast helicopters to attack nuclear submarines which may be faster than surface warships.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] For this task the helicopter is equipped with sensors such as sonobuoys, wire-mounted dipping sonar and magnetic anomaly detectors to identify possible threats, and torpedoes or depth-charges to attack them.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] With their onboard radar helicopters can also be used to reconnoitre over-the-horizon targets and, if equipped with anti-ship missiles such as Penguin or Sea Skua, to attack them.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] The helicopter is also invaluable for search and rescue operation and has largely replaced the use of small boats or the jackstay rig for such duties as transferring personnel, mail and cargo between ships or to shore.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] With helicopters these tasks can be accomplished faster and less dangerously, and without the need for the frigate to slow down or change course.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] Frigates designed in the 1960s and 1970s, such as the US Navy's *Knox*-class frigate, West Germany's *Bremen*-class frigate, and Royal Navy's Type 22 frigate were equipped with a small number of short-ranged surface-to-air missiles (Sea Sparrow or Sea Wolf) for point defence only.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] By contrast newer frigates starting with the *Oliver Hazard Perry*-class frigate are specialised for "zone-defence" air defence, because of major developments in fighter jets and cruise missiles.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] Recent examples include the *De Zeven Provinciën*-class air defence and command frigate of the Royal Netherlands Navy.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] Another example is the *Iver Huitfeldt* class of the Royal Danish Navy.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] Some new classes of ships similar to corvettes are optimized for high-speed deployment and combat with small craft rather than combat between equal opponents; an example is the U.S. littoral combat ship (LCS).
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] As of 2015, all *Oliver Hazard Perry*-class frigates in the United States Navy have been decommissioned, and their role partially assumed by the new LCS.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] While the LCS class ships are smaller than the frigate class they will replace, they offer a similar degree of weaponry while requiring less than half the crew complement and offering a top speed of over 40 knots (74 km/h; 46 mph).
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] A major advantage for the LCS ships is that they are designed around specific mission modules allowing them to fulfil a variety of roles.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] The modular system also allows for most upgrades to be performed ashore and installed later into the ship, keeping the ships available for deployment for the maximum time.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] The latest U.S. deactivation plans make this the first time that the U.S.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] Navy has been without a frigate class of ships since 1943 (technically USS *Constitution* is rated as a frigate and is still in commission, but does not count towards Navy force levels).
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] The remaining 20 LCSs to be acquired from 2019 and onwards that will be enhanced will be designated as frigates, and existing ships given modifications may also have their classification changed to *FF* as well.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] However, the United States Navy selected a FREMM multipurpose frigate variant for a new *Constellation* class of 20 frigates, to be built by Fincantieri beginning in 2024.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] Stealth technology has been introduced in modern frigate design by the French *La Fayette* class design.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] Frigate shapes are designed to offer a minimal radar cross section, which also lends them good air penetration; the manoeuvrability of these frigates has been compared to that of sailing ships.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] The modern French Navy applies the term first-class frigate and second-class frigate to both destroyers and frigates in service.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] Pennant numbers remain divided between F-series numbers for those ships internationally recognised as frigates and D-series pennant numbers for those more traditionally recognised as destroyers.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] This can result in some confusion as certain classes are referred to as frigates in French service while similar ships in other navies are referred to as destroyers.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] This also results in some recent classes of French ships such as the Horizon class being among the largest in the world to carry the rating of frigate.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] The *Frégates de Taille Intermédiaire* (FTI), which means frigates of intermediate size, is a French military program to design and create a planned class of frigates to be used by the French Navy.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] At the moment, the program consists of five ships, with commissioning planned from 2023.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] In the German Navy, frigates were used to replace ageing destroyers; however in size and role the new German frigates exceed the former class of destroyers.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] The current German F125 Baden-Württemberg-class frigates are the largest class of frigates worldwide with a displacement of more than 7,200 tons .
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] The same was done in the Spanish Navy, which went ahead with the deployment of the first Aegis frigates, the *Álvaro de Bazán*-class frigates.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] The Myanmar Navy is producing modern frigates with a reduced radar cross section known as the Kyan Sittha-class frigate.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] Before the Kyan Sittha class, the Myanmar Navy also produced an *Aung Zeya*-class frigate.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] Although the size of the Myanmar Navy is quite small, it is producing modern guided-missile frigates with the help of Russia, China, and India.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] However, the fleets of the Myanmar Navy are still expanding with several on-going shipbuilding programmes, including one 135 m (442 ft 11 in), 4,000-tonne frigate with the vertical missile launch systems.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] The four planned *Tamandaré*-class frigates of the Brazilian Navy will be responsible for introducing ships with stealth technology in the national navy and the Latin American region, with the first boat expected to be launched in 2024.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] A few frigates have survived as museum ships.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/armored-frigate-p01] These ships are classified by their respective nations as frigates, but are considered destroyers internationally due to size, armament, and role.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-cherbourg] Cherbourg had been a stronghold since Roman times, and was one of the strongest fortresses of the Hundred Years War.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-cherbourg] But until the 18th century it had only a shallow harbour, minor commercial activity and no military development.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-cherbourg] In the 17th century the military engineer Vauban drew up plans to develop Cherbourg into a port where passing ships could shelter from attack or storms.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-cherbourg] Vauban's plans included an artificial harbour, and the quadrupling of the size of the city.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-cherbourg] The project was eventually abandoned, before being temporarily revived under Louis XV.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-cherbourg] The British raid on Cherbourg in 1758 however caused severe damage to the barely completed commercial port.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-cherbourg] By the 1770s, with French involvement in the American War of Independence, Louis XVI sought to create a large military port on the Cotentin Peninsula, allowing access into the English Channel, and comparable to that of Brest on the Atlantic.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-cherbourg] Two projects were drawn up and presented to the king in 1777.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-cherbourg] The first, by the chief engineer of the bridges, roads and ports of the Caen region, Armand Lefebvre, called for the fortification of the Cherbourg roadstead around the enlarged commercial port.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-cherbourg] The second project, by director of maritime engineering Antoine Choquet de Lindu, proposed the construction of a first class arsenal at La Hougue.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-cherbourg] Naval officer Louis de La Couldre de La Bretonnière conducted a review of the proposals, which favoured the Cherbourg option.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-cherbourg] La Bretonnière recommended the construction of a jetty "two thousand toises long" between the tip of Querqueville and the reefs of Île Pelée, with the dredging of a harbour to a depth of 20 meters.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-cherbourg] La Bretonnière suggested the construction of a breakwater composed of sunken hulks and rocks, to be a foundation for further construction.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-cherbourg] Ultimately an alternative proposal, by engineer Louis-Alexandre de Cessart, was preferred, that of a breakwater created by the sinking of 90 wooden cones weighted with stones, 50 meters in diameter at the base and 20 meters in height.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-cherbourg] Work began in the 1780s. Île Pelée was fortified, and the wooden cones filled with stone were sunk outside the harbour(one in the presence of the king), to serve as a foundation for the breakwater.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-cherbourg] The cones were damaged by bad weather, and were gradually replaced by a continuous breakwater in pierres perdues, when the works were interrupted by the French Revolution.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-cherbourg] Work resumed in 1803 under the orders of First Consul Napoleon Bonaparte (decree of 25 Germinal year XI), as part of the plans to invade the United Kingdom.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-cherbourg] From 1803, protected from British attacks, Cherbourg became a haven for privateers.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-cherbourg] The breakwater was discontinued after 1813, to be resumed in 1830 and completed in 1853.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-cherbourg] The engineer Joseph Cachin continued building the military port to the west of the town, the avant-port of which was opened on 27 August 1813 by Empress Marie-Louise.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-cherbourg] It was decided to establish the Arsenal in the same place.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-cherbourg] Work began on the Charles X basin (420 × 200 × 18 meters) in 1814, and it was inaugurated on 25 August 1829 in the presence of the Dauphin.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-cherbourg] A second basin, Napoleon III (290 × 220 × 18 meters), was begun in 1836 and inaugurated on 7 August 1858 in the presence of Napoleon III and Empress Eugénie.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-cherbourg] The continuous expansion of the military port and dockyard eventually came to consume between 3 and 4 million gold francs a year.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-cherbourg] By the end of the nineteenth century the United Kingdom was no longer the main adversary.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-cherbourg] The city had become a major industrial centre and employer, with 4,000 workers from all over France based at the arsenal, which became the "backbone of the city".
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-cherbourg] With the naval importance of the port reduced, the well-developed harbour became a base for transatlantic trade connecting northern Europe with the east coast of the Americas.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-cherbourg] The city was first bombed by the *Luftwaffe* on 15 June 1940, during the Battle of France.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-cherbourg] The port was used as the evacuation point as British and French soldiers withdrew ahead of the advancing German Army, Cherbourg becoming the "Norman Dunkirk".
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-cherbourg] The east fort on the breakwater was destroyed by the French Navy.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-cherbourg] German forces arrived at Cherbourg on 17 June, and on 18 June the city council declared Cherbourg an open city.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-cherbourg] Maritime prefect Vice-Admiral Jules Le Bigot ensured three submarines under construction at the arsenal, *Praya*, *Roland Morillot* and *Martinique*, were destroyed, and then surrendered the city to General Erwin Rommel.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-cherbourg] Cherbourg, the only deep-water port in the region, was the primary goal of US troops landed at Utah Beach during the allied invasion of Normandy.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-cherbourg] Cherbourg was vital in order to provide the Allies logistical support for the reinforcement and supply of the troops.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-cherbourg] US troops encircled the city on 21 June 1944.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-cherbourg] Furious street fighting took place, with heavy supporting fire from allied warships against the German batteries.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-cherbourg] After strong resistance from Fort du Roule, General Karl-Wilhelm von Schlieben, Admiral Walter Hennecke and 37,000 soldiers surrendered on 26 June at 16:00 to General J.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-cherbourg] The arsenal and the forts on the breakwater resisted for another day before they too surrendered.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-cherbourg] The Germans had systematically damaged the port prior to surrendering.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-cherbourg] Ships, tugs, cranes and other equipment had been thrown into the water in the basins, blocking the harbour and delaying the arrival of the first ships until the end of July.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-cherbourg] In November 1944, the local Cherbourg bailout commission was created to organise the salvaging of ships and clearing accesses to the port.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-cherbourg] The port was only partially back in service by mid-August.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-cherbourg] On 14 July 1944 the Place du Château, renamed Place du Maréchal-Pétain during the German occupation, was renamed Place Général De Gaulle, while the Quai de l'Ancien-Arsenal was renamed Lawton-Collins Quay, after the American commander of VII Corps, which had liberated the city.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-cherbourg] American troops of the Fourth Major Port of Embarkation and French transport corps carried out sufficient repairs to the port for it to accommodate the first liberty ships a month after its capture.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-cherbourg] From then until the liberation of the port of Antwerp in November 1944, the daily landing of supplies and military equipment made Cherbourg the largest port in the world, twice that of the port of New York.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-cherbourg] Fuel arrived in Cherbourg along the PLUTO pipeline, while men and the equipment were routed from the port to the front, travelling by road (the "Red Ball Express") and rail (the "Toot Sweet Express").
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-cherbourg] On 24 December 1944, the Belgian freighter SS *Léopoldville*, carrying 2,237 American soldiers of the 66th Infantry Division, was torpedoed by a German submarine off Cherbourg.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-cherbourg] Cherbourg was returned to France by the Americans on 14 October 1945.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-cherbourg] It is quoted in the order of the army of 2 June 1948 and was awarded the Croix de Guerre with palm.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-cherbourg] Cherbourg is one of three naval bases of metropolitan France (the other two are Brest and Toulon).
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-cherbourg] With the departure of the Flotilla of the North (FLONOR), Cherbourg lost its importance as a port of registry.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-cherbourg] The Channel Flotilla (Flomanche) monitors the English Channel and the North Sea.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-cherbourg] The arsenal of Cherbourg specializes in submarine construction.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-cherbourg] These are nuclear vessels for the French Navy, such as the *Triomphant* class and the planned *Suffren* class, or conventional diesel-electric propulsion vessels for export, such as the Scorpène type.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-cherbourg] Faced with declining needs, the Navy has since 2000 opened the arsenal to the private sector.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-cherbourg] It leases 50,000 m2 (540,000 sq ft) of land to two companies in its northern part: the Euriware secure management centre (100 employees) and the Ican shipyard (170 employees), specializing in the construction of service boats.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-toulon] The **military port of Toulon** (French: *arsenal de Toulon*) is the principal base of the French Navy and the largest naval base in the Mediterranean and Western Europe, situated in the city of Toulon.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-toulon] It holds most of France's force d'action navale, comprising the aircraft carrier *Charles de Gaulle* as well as its nuclear attack submarines, in total, the base contains more than 60% of the French Navy's tonnage, and about 20,000 military and civilian personnel work at the base.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-toulon] The word *rade* comes from the old English term 'Road,' "a protected place near shore, not so enclosed as a harbour, where ships can ride at anchor.".
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-toulon] The Rade of Toulon is one of the best natural anchorages on the Mediterranean, and the largest rade in Europe.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-toulon] It is protected from the sea by the peninsula of Giens and the peninsula of Saint-Mandrier-sur-Mer, and has been used as a military harbour since the 15th century.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-toulon] The Rade shelters the port of Saint-Mandrier-sur-Mer, the port of La Seyne-sur-Mer, as well as the arsenal, or military port of Toulon, and the commercial port.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-toulon] The 'modern' history of the port began when Louis XII built his Tour Royale at Toulon in 1514.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-toulon] A naval arsenal and shipyard were built in 1599, and small sheltered harbour, the Veille Darse, was built in 1604–1610 to protect ships from the wind and sea.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-toulon] The shipyard was greatly enlarged by Cardinal Richelieu, who wished to make France into a Mediterranean naval power.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-toulon] In 1680, Jean-Baptiste Colbert, Secretary of State of the Navy and Controller of Finance of King Louis XIV, began building a much larger port, called the Darse Vauban or the Darse Neuve, and shipyard, designed by his commissioner of fortifications, Vauban.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-toulon] In 1697, Vauban built the impressive corderie, a building designed to make ropes.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-toulon] The corderie, still standing, is 20 metres wide and 320 metres long, built so that ropes could be stretched the entire length of the building as they were twisted together.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-toulon] Power for the ropemaking was provided by convicts from the adjoining prison, the Bagne de Toulon, who walked in an enormous treadmill.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-toulon] A triumphal gate (now the Museum of the Navy) was added to the Arsenal in 1738.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-toulon] The Arsenal port was enlarged still further in the 19th century and the 20th century.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-toulon] The construction of the arsenal du Mourillon began at the start of the 18th century, as an extension of the major Toulon arsenal on the roadstead's east coast.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-toulon] Until the 20th century this extension held stores for the wood to build the French Navy.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-toulon] From the late 19th century it was this shipyard that built France's first ironclad frigates then the world's first modern submarines.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-toulon] Rather than joining the Free French forces in North Africa and to avoid capture by the Germans, the French fleet based at Toulon scuttled itself on 27 November 1942 on the orders of the French admiralty.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-toulon] During the 20th century the Mourillon arsenal was mainly dedicated to submarine activity as a French submarine base until 1940, then a German one from 1940 to 1945, then a dockyard and torpedo factory after 1945.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-toulon] The Arsenal was badly damaged by Allied bombing in World War II, but since has been reconstructed and modernised.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-toulon] It has eleven drydocks for ship repair, the two largest of which are 422 metres by 40 metres.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-toulon] The Arsenal is still the principal military port of France, the home port of the aircraft carrier *Charles de Gaulle,* France's attack submarine squadron, and the other ships of the French Mediterranean fleet.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-toulon] The Arsenal is not open to the public, but the Naval Museum at its entrance has a collection of enormous ship models from the 18th century, used to train the heir to the throne in seamanship, as well as other naval memorabilia.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-toulon] The building of the Corderie can be seen beside the road nearby.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-toulon] Boat tours depart regularly from the waterfront, and allow visitors to have a good look at ships of the French fleet.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-toulon] The military base is divided into four main zones, each with their own access to the sea.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-toulon] The three other gates are secondary and little used, though still heavily guarded.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-toulon] To the extreme west in the communes of La Seyne-sur-Mer and Ollioules the military base is in contact with the commercial port of Brégaillon, connected to national and regional networks for the supply of artillery munitions and other supplies.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-toulon] The arsenal du Mourillon, next to the roadstead, is directly accessible via the north arsenal which housed a submarine base until 1945.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-toulon] The south arsenal is accessed by the small slipway of Le Mourillon beside the now-disappeared torpedo factory.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-toulon] The military bases possesses more than 30 km of roads, railway level crossings, traffic lights, signs, etc..
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-toulon] It also has an SNCF rail line running from the station at La Seyne-sur-Mer to the docks via its storage sheds.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-toulon] Used to harbour foreign ships, or large ships.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-toulon] Traditionally, this quay was used to honour distinguished ships by putting them into view from the merchant harbour.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-toulon] The four dry docks are fit for repairs on medium to large craft.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-toulon] The Vaudan dock is used as a mooring for small ships (diver support, mine warfare, tugs, patrol boats) and elder ships.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-toulon] The quays are fitted with mobile roofs that cover the submarines when their nuclear equipment is being refitted.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-toulon] These quays also comprise a number of dry docks.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/arsenal-de-toulon] The main mooring stations of the harbour, where frigates, aircraft carriers, fleet tankers and landing ships are stationed.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/artillery-battery] The term is also used in a naval context to describe groups of guns on warships.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/artillery-battery] Historically the term "battery" referred to a cluster of cannons in action as a group, either in a temporary field position during a battle or at the siege of a fortress or a city.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/artillery-battery] Such batteries could be a mixture of cannon, howitzer, or mortar types.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/artillery-battery] A siege could involve many batteries at different sites around the besieged place.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/artillery-battery] The term also came to be used for a group of cannons in a fixed fortification, for coastal or frontier defence.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/artillery-battery] During the 18th century "battery" began to be used as an organizational term for a permanent unit of artillery in peace and war, although horse artillery sometimes used "troop" and fixed position artillery "company".
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/artillery-battery] They were usually organised with between 6 and 12 ordnance pieces, often including cannon and howitzers.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/artillery-battery] By the late 19th century "battery" had become standard mostly replacing company or troop.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/artillery-battery] In the 20th century the term was generally used for the company level sub-unit of an artillery branch including field, air-defence, anti-tank and position (coastal and frontier defences).
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/artillery-battery] 20th-century firing batteries have been equipped with mortars, guns, howitzers, rockets and missiles.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/artillery-battery] During the Napoleonic Wars some armies started grouping their batteries into larger administrative and field units.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/artillery-battery] Groups of batteries combined for field combat employment called Grand Batteries by Napoleon.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/artillery-battery] Administratively batteries were usually grouped in battalions, regiments or squadrons and these developed into tactical organisations.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/artillery-battery] These were further grouped into regiments, simply "group" or brigades, that may be wholly composed of artillery units or combined arms in composition.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/artillery-battery] To further concentrate fire of individual batteries, from World War I they were grouped into "artillery divisions" in a few armies.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/artillery-battery] Coastal artillery sometimes had completely different organizational terms based on shore defence sector areas.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/artillery-battery] Batteries also have sub-divisions, which vary across armies and periods but often translate into the English "platoon" or "troop" with individual ordnance systems called a "section" or "sub-section", where a section comprises two artillery pieces.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/artillery-battery] The rank of a battery commander has also varied, but is usually a lieutenant, captain, or major.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/artillery-battery] The number of guns, howitzers, mortars or launchers in an organizational battery has also varied, with the calibre of guns usually being an important consideration.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/artillery-battery] In the 19th century four to 12 guns was usual as the optimum number to maneuver into the gun line.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/artillery-battery] By the late 19th century, a mountain artillery battery was divided into a gun line and an ammunition line.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/artillery-battery] The gun line consisted of six guns (five mules to a gun) and 12 ammunition mules.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/artillery-battery] During the American Civil War, artillery batteries often consisted of six field pieces for the Union Army and four for the Confederate States Army, although this varied.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/artillery-battery] Batteries were divided into sections of two guns apiece, each section normally under the command of a lieutenant.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/artillery-battery] The full battery was typically commanded by a captain.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/artillery-battery] Often, particularly as the war progressed, individual batteries were grouped into battalions under a major or colonel of artillery.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/artillery-battery] In the 20th century it varied between four and 12 for field artillery (even 16 if mortars), or even two pieces for very heavy pieces.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/artillery-battery] Other types of artillery such as anti-tank or anti-aircraft have sometimes been larger.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/artillery-battery] Some batteries have been "dual-equipped" with two different types of gun or mortar, and taking whichever was more appropriate when they deployed for operations.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/artillery-battery] From the late 19th century field artillery batteries started to become more complex organisations.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/artillery-battery] First they needed the capability to carry adequate ammunition, typically each gun could only carry about 40 rounds in its limber so additional wagons were added to the battery, typically about two per gun.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/artillery-battery] This in turn led to the need for signalers, which further increased as the need to concentrate the fire of dispersed batteries emerged and the introduction fire control staff at artillery headquarters above the batteries.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/artillery-battery] Fixed artillery refers to guns or howitzers on mounts that were either anchored in one spot (though capable of being moved for purposes of traverse and elevation), or on carriages intended to be moved only for the purposes of aiming, and not for tactical repositioning.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/artillery-battery] Historical versions often closely resembled naval cannon of their day, "garrison carriages," like naval carriages, were short, heavy, and had four small wheels meant for rolling on relatively smooth, hard surfaces.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/artillery-battery] Later, both naval and garrison carriages evolved traversing platforms and pivoting mounts.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/artillery-battery] Such mounts were typically used in forts, or permanent defensive batteries, such as coastal artillery.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/artillery-battery] Fixed batteries could be equipped with much larger guns than field artillery units could transport, and the gun emplacement was only one part of an extensive installation that included magazines and systems to deliver ammunition from the magazines to the guns.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/artillery-battery] Improvements in mobile artillery, naval and ground; air attack; and precision guided weapons have limited fixed position's usefulness.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/artillery-battery] "Battery" is a relatively modern term at sea.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/artillery-battery] Advanced warships in the Age of Sail, such as the ship of the line, mounted dozens of similar cannons grouped in broadsides, sometimes spread over several decks.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/artillery-battery] This remained the standard main weapon layout for centuries, until the mid-19th century evolution of the naval rifle and revolving gun turrets came to displace fixed cannon.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/artillery-battery] The first operational use of a rotating turret was on the American ironclad USS *Monitor*, designed during the American Civil War by John Ericsson.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/artillery-battery] Open barbettes were also used to house their main batteries on rotating mounts.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/artillery-battery] Both designs allowed naval engineers to dramatically reduce the number of guns present in the battery, by giving a handful of guns the ability to concentrate on either side of the ship.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/artillery-battery] In time this trend reversed, with a proliferation of weapons of multiple calibers being arranged somewhat haphazardly about a vessel, many in mounts on the hull or superstructure with limited travel.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/artillery-battery] Confusion also arose when combinations of large caliber "main battery" and smaller "secondary battery" weapons of mixed offensive and defensive use were deployed.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/artillery-battery] This began to be resolved with the 1906 launching of the revolutionary "all big gun" battleship HMS *Dreadnought*.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/artillery-battery] It shipped a main battery of ten heavy caliber guns, and a smaller secondary battery for self-defense.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/artillery-battery] A third, or tertiary battery, of weapons lighter than the secondary battery was typically mounted.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/artillery-battery] To simplify the design many later ships used dual-purpose guns to combine the functions of the secondary battery and the heavier guns of the tertiary batteries.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/artillery-battery] Many dual-purpose guns also served in an anti-aircraft role.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/artillery-battery] In addition, dedicated light-caliber rapid-fire anti-aircraft weapons were deployed, often in the scores.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/artillery-battery] Conventional artillery as a vessel's battery has been largely displaced by guided missiles for both offensive and defensive actions.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/artillery-battery] Small caliber guns are retained for niche roles, such as the multi-barrel Phalanx CIWS rotary cannon used for point defense.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/artillery-battery] The rapid fire 5"/54 caliber Mark 45 gun 5-inch (130 mm) and Otobreda 76 mm (3.0 in) used for close defense against surface combatants and shore bombardment are among the last traditional naval guns still in use.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/artillery-battery] In modern battery organization, the military unit typically has six to eight howitzers or six to nine rocket launchers and 100 to 200 personnel and is the equivalent of a company in terms of organisation level.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/artillery-battery] In the United States Army, generally a towed howitzer battery has six guns, whereas a self-propelled battery (such as an M109 battery) contains eight.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/artillery-battery] The battery is typically commanded by a captain in US forces and is equivalent to an infantry company.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/artillery-battery] Other armies can be significantly different, however.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/artillery-battery] The United Kingdom and Commonwealth forces have classified batteries according to the caliber of the guns.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/artillery-battery] Headquarters batteries, which themselves have no artillery pieces, but are rather the command and control organization for a group of firing batteries (for example, a regimental or battalion headquarters battery).
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/artillery-battery] The basic field organization being the "gun group" and the "tactical group".
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/artillery-battery] The former being reconnaissance and survey, guns, command posts, logistic and equipment support elements, the latter being the battery commander and observation teams that deploy with the supported arm.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/artillery-battery] In these armies the guns may be split into several fire units, which may deploy dispersed over an extended area or be concentrated into a single position.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/artillery-battery] In some cases batteries have operationally deployed as six totally separate guns, although sections (pairs) are more usual.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/artillery-battery] A battery commander, or "BC" is a Major (like his infantry company commander counterpart).
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/artillery-battery] However, in these armies the battery commander leads the "tactical group" and is usually located with the headquarters of the infantry or armoured unit the battery is supporting.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/artillery-battery] Increasingly these direct support battery commanders are responsible for the orchestration of all forms of fire support (mortars, attack helicopters, other aircraft and naval gunfire) as well as artillery.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/artillery-battery] General support battery commanders are likely to be at brigade or higher headquarters.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/artillery-battery] The gun group is commanded by the Battery Captain (BK), the battery's second-in-command.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/artillery-battery] However this position has no technical responsibilities, its primary concern is administration, including ammunition supply, local defence and is based in the "wagon-lines" a short distance from the actual gun position, where the gun towing and logistic vehicles are concealed.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/artillery-battery] Technical control is by the Gun Position Officer (GPO, a lieutenant) who is also the reconnaissance officer.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/artillery-battery] The battery has two Command Posts (CP), one active and one alternate, the latter provides back-up in the event of casualties, but primarily moves with the preparation party to the next gun position and becomes the main CP there.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/artillery-battery] Each CP is controlled by a Command Post Officer (CPO) who is usually a Lieutenant, 2nd Lieutenant or Warrant Officer Class 2.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/artillery-battery] Gun positions may be "tight", perhaps 150 m × 150 m (490 ft × 490 ft) when the counter battery threat is low, or gun manoeuver areas, where pairs of self-propelled guns move around a far larger area, if the counter-battery threat is high.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/artillery-battery] During the Cold War NATO batteries that were dedicated to a nuclear role generally operated as "sections" comprising a single gun or launcher.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/artillery-battery] Groupings of mortars, when they are not operated by artillery, are usually referred to as platoons.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/artillery-battery] For example: the basic field organization being the "gun group" and the "tactical group".
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/artillery-battery] The former being reconnaissance and survey, guns, command posts, logistic, and equipment support elements, the latter being the battery commander and observation teams that deploy with the supported arm.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/artillery-battery] It some cases batteries have operationally deployed as six totally separate guns, although sections (pairs) are more usual.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/gloire-class-ironclad] The ***Gloire*-class ironclads** were a group of three wooden-hulled armored frigates built for the French Navy in the late 1850s and early 1860s.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/gloire-class-ironclad] *Gloire*, the lead ship of the class, was the first ocean-going ironclad warship to be built by any country.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/gloire-class-ironclad] The ships of the *Gloire* class were classified as armoured frigates because they only had a single gun deck and their traditional disposition of guns arrayed along the length of the hull also meant that they were broadside ironclads.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/gloire-class-ironclad] Designed by the French naval architect Henri Dupuy de Lôme, the ships of the class were intended to fight in the line of battle, unlike the first British ironclads.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/gloire-class-ironclad] The ships of the class had a high metacentric height of 2.1 meters (7 ft) and consequently rolled badly.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/gloire-class-ironclad] With their gun ports only 1.88 meters (6 ft 2 in) above the waterline, they proved to be very wet.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/gloire-class-ironclad] They had a crew of 570 officers and enlisted men.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/gloire-class-ironclad] The ships of the *Gloire* class had a single horizontal return connecting-rod compound steam engine that drove a six-bladed, 5.8-meter (19 ft 0 in) propeller.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/gloire-class-ironclad] The engine was powered by eight Indret oval boilers and was designed for a capacity of 2,500 indicated horsepower (1,900 kW).
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/gloire-class-ironclad] On sea trials, the ships exceeded 13 knots (24 km/h; 15 mph).
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/gloire-class-ironclad] They carried a maximum of 675 metric tons (664 long tons) of coal which allowed them to steam for 4,000 kilometers (2,500 mi) at a speed of 8 knots (15 km/h; 9.2 mph).
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/gloire-class-ironclad] The *Gloire*-class ships were initially fitted with a light barquentine rig with three masts that had a sail area around 1,100 square metres (11,800 sq ft).
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/gloire-class-ironclad] This was later changed to a full ship rig of 2,500 square meters (27,000 sq ft), but later had to be reduced because of excessive rolling.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/gloire-class-ironclad] The ships were initially armed with 36 Modèle 1858 164.7-millimeter (6.5 in) rifled muzzle-loading guns, 34（14 each sides and 2 pivot mounts fore and 4 pivot mounts aft as chase guns）of which were positioned on the single gun deck in the broadside.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/gloire-class-ironclad] The remaining two guns were placed on the upper deck as chase guns.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/gloire-class-ironclad] They fired a 44.9-kilogram (99.0 lb) shell at a muzzle velocity of only 322 meters per second (1,060 ft/s) and proved to be ineffective against armour.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/gloire-class-ironclad] They were replaced by rifled breech-loading Modèle 1864 guns in 1868.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/gloire-class-ironclad] Six Canon de 24 C modèle 1864 guns were mounted in the middle of the gun deck and on the upper deck two 194-millimeter (7.6 in) guns replaced the original chase guns.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/gloire-class-ironclad] The wooden hull was completely armoured with wrought iron plates 120 millimeters (4.7 in) thick.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/gloire-class-ironclad] Backed by the 760-millimeter (30 in) sides of the hull, the armour extended 5.4 meters (17 ft 9 in) above the waterline and 2.0 meters (6 ft 7 in) below.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/gloire-class-ironclad] The *Gloire*-class ships had an open-topped conning tower with armour 100 millimeters (3.9 in) thick and 10 millimeters (0.4 in) of armour underneath the wooden upper deck.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/gloire-class-ironclad] All three ships of the class had very uneventful careers, spending the bulk of their time with the Mediterranean Fleet aside from a few excursions to foreign waters.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/gloire-class-ironclad] *Normandie* supported the French intervention in Mexico in 1862, the first ironclad to cross the Atlantic.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/gloire-class-ironclad] They were active during the Franco-Prussian War, but saw no action.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/gloire-class-ironclad] *Gloire*, the only ship built with seasoned timber lasted the longest, not being condemned and broken up until 1879.
[src:gloire-class-ironclad/gloire-class-ironclad] Her sister ships only lasted a decade in service before they were too rotten for any further use and were condemned in 1871–1872 and subsequently broken up.
